[[File:Massa marittima, fonte e palazzo dell'abbondanza, albero della fecondità, 1265 circa 03.JPG|thumb|Phallus tree in the Fertility Fresco at [[Massa Marittima]], circa 1265]]

The '''phallus tree''' was an art motif common in [[Western Europe]] during the late [[Middle Ages]] and the beginning of the [[Renaissance]].<ref>''The Phallus Tree: A Medieval and Renaissance Phenomenon'', Johan J. Mattelaer, MD, 14 January 2010, {{DOI|10.1111/j.1743-6109.2009.01668.x}}</ref>

Its concrete significance is hazy, but it appeared in bronze, illuminated manuscript, and paint; it manifested as bawdy humour, religious parody, political comment. The Tuscan Massa Marittima mural, featuring oversized phalluses, some erect, complete with testes, was [[Guelphs and Ghibellines|Guelph]] propaganda warning that if the [[Ghibellines]] were allowed to take control, they would bring with them sexual perversion and witchcraft.

