{{italic title}} [[Image:Parrish-911-detail.jpg|thumb|''The Cycle of Terror and Tragedy'' (detail) by Graydon Parrish]] '''''The Cycle of Terror and Tragedy''''' is a painting by [[Graydon Parrish]].
==History== In 2002, Douglas Hyland, the director of the [[New Britain Museum of American Art]], approached [[Graydon Parrish]] to create an allegorical tribute to the [[September 11 attacks]]. The completed painting, ''The Cycle of Terror and Tragedy'', is over 18 feet long and is one of the largest realist paintings ever created in America. Today it hangs in the Chase Wing of the New Britain Museum of American Art.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbmaa.wordpress.com/2010/09/10/collection-highlights-the-cycle-of-terror-and-tragedy-september-11-2001/|title=The Cycle of Terror and Tragedy: September 11, 2001|work=New Britain Museum of American Art}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nbmaa.wordpress.com/2010/02/11/collection-highlights-the-cycle-of-terror-and-tragedy-september-11-2001/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100427042250/http://nbmaa.wordpress.com/2010/02/11/collection-highlights-the-cycle-of-terror-and-tragedy-september-11-2001/ |archivedate=2010-04-27 |df= }}</ref>
==Reception== The painting has been noted for its [[Academic art|academic style]], inspired both by [[Jacques-Louis David]] and [[William-Adolphe Bouguereau|William Bouguereau]], and for its highly symbolic content, said to express the cycle of denial and tragedy. It has been compared and contrasted with [[Pablo Picasso]]'s ''[[Guernica (painting)|Guernica]]'' and [[Théodore Géricault]]'s ''[[The Raft of the Medusa]]'', both comments on [[Disaster|catastrophes]]. A review in ''[[The New York Times]]'' summarized that "Mr. Parrish has a fine arsenal of talent and ideas, but this particular work comes off as overly staged, showy and annoyingly melodramatic, the clichéd pomp and classical symbolism drowning out a gentler, more compassionate spirit."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/18/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/18ctarts.html?ex=1179201600&en=16a99e55f8182ad2&ei=5070 |first=Benjamin |last=Genocchio|authorlink=Benjamin Genocchio|title= The Tragedy of 9/11, on a Long Sheet of Canvas|newspaper=New York Times|date= 18 February 2007}}</ref> [[James Panero]], writing in ''[[The New Criterion]]'', believed "The cycle of terror and tragedy: September 11, 2001," is a pretty good painting that manages to be monumentally terrible."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newcriterion.com/posts.cfm/graydon-parrishs-cycle-of-terror-4351|title=Graydon Parrish&rsquo;s &rsquo;Cycle of Terror&rsquo; by James Panero - The New Criterion|work=newcriterion.com}}</ref> In response, Aimee Pozorski wrote that "In fact, it is true that what Parrish has created is a lovely and symmetrical allegory: The twin bodies--strong, virile, and painted as if part of a [[Botticelli]] painting--are also allegories for the virile twin towers about to fall. The children holding planes represent the loss of innocence of an entire nation."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vwmSBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145&dq=graydon+parrish+9/11&source=bl&ots=Y7LC_oyABx&sig=BRwJbbrenP_NtzuN6tVEasHp5nE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XW_iVIzbI8TBggSo9oC4DQ&ved=0CEYQ6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=graydon%20parrish%209%2F11&f=false|title=Falling After 9/11|work=google.com}}</ref>
